tip.text: OMG best lunch of my Puglia trip. The eponymous aunts serve deceptively simple but oh so flavorsome food in their living room restaurant. Get the antipasti and the lamb. You'll die.
Slightly fancy but high quality food. The antipasti della casa might kill you before getting to your primi.
The antipasti are a steal. They also have some good modern style beers. I enjoyed the APA.
Excellent place to sample a range of Lebanese dishes. We had hummus, falafel salad and a trio of cheese manoush and enjoyed it all. Would like to go back to try other stuff.

formattedAddress: Ground Floor, Jumeira Tower (Sheikh Zayed Road)

tip.text: Went for the chopan kebab: tender pieces of grilled mutton rack and ribs. Tasty.
Shawarma hits the spot. So good you might go for seconds.
Had a tasty set lunch of Cambodian food. Most dishes can be made vegetarian. Seating is outdoors in a pleasant garden with (yes) lots of butterflies and a big fish pond.
This is probably not the correct venue but I am leaving this here anyway. On Dao Duy Tu street in the morning there is a lady selling banh cuon from a tiny streetside restaurant. It is very good.
Good place to sample Bún Thang.
Amazing food. Must try when in HCMC, they specialize in southern Vietnamese dishes such as Trang Bang Rice Paper.

venue.name: Bánh Tráng Trảng Bàng Hoàng Ty

tip.text: Delicious food, tidy space and devoted service. Good for lunch. Many vegetarian options available.
Great for getting your bakso fix. I had a mie polos on the side. Very satisfying.
Generous portions and very tasty. I had the duck rice. Worth queueing for.

formattedAddress: #01-24, Zion Riverside Food Centre (70 Zion Rd.)

venue.name: Boon Tong Kee Kway Chap Braised Duck

tip.text: Food is attractively presented and tasty. Clearly aimed at tourists. One of few decent dinner options in this part of town I guess.

contact.facebookName: Red Dragon Restaurant, Hoi An, Vietnam

tip.text: Barring inconsiderate clientele and street noise this is a refuge from the ancient town tourist crush. Delicious teas. The cookie sampler is worth it, too.
Returned twice since my previous tip for food and can say it is much better than the coffee. Particularly partial to the breakfast offerings.
I'm a sucker for Buddhist art so enjoyed the first sections. Communist art in the later parts gets a bit monotonous. The craftsmanship, particularly of the lacquerwork, is undeniable though.

venue.name: Bảo Tàng Mỹ Thuật Việt Nam (Vietnam Fine Arts Museum)

tip.text: Nowhere in Vietnam have a queued as long for food as here but by golly was it worth it. Aromatic, complex broth. Tasty beef and noodle just the right bite. Make sure you get some fritters on the side.
Location can't be beat. It's comfortable, affordable, not too big and the staff is friendly. My favorite place to stay in Surabaya.
Had a pretty fantastic dim sum lunch here. Make sure you try the You Tiao wrapped in Chee Cheong Fun. An unholy combo that shouldn't work but somehow does.

formattedAddress: #05-12 Ngee Ann City Takashimaya (391 Orchard Road)

tip.text: The dumplings at #01-31 Shanghai La Mian Xiao Long Bao are crazy good.
All the cooking is done on a charcoal stove. If you want to feel like you've gone back to the Singapore of 20 years ago, come for a kopi and kaya toast here.
Great place to sample Bún bò Huế, the city's signature beef noodle. A breakfast dish, so make sure you come early.
They do health and fitness lifestyle food—low carb, high protein, low GI, etc. You can build your own or order a set. Not bad, but not great either.
If you're feeling peckish the salted egg dumpling will sort you right out. Make sure you come early because they are popular and usually run out by the beginning of the afternoon.

formattedAddress: #01-18. Amoy Street Food Center (7 Maxwell Road)

tip.text: Come inside and be wowed by the enormous Buddha statue.

venue.name: Temple Of 1000 Lights (Sakya Muni Buddha Gaya Temple)

tip.text: Impressive building with an interior to match. Worth a visit if only to take a breather from the Chinatown bustle outside.

formattedAddress: 288 South Bridge Road (South Bridge Road / Sago Lane)

venue.name: Buddha Tooth Relic Temple & Museum (新加坡佛牙寺龙华院)

tip.text: Top grades for authentic atmosphere by they don't slice the kaya toast and you need to break your own eggs so quality wise it's not amazing. Still a fun place to take out of towners to for breakfast.

venue.name: Tong Ah Eating House 东亚

tip.text: I didn't care much for the interior or atmosphere but they did make me a decent old fashioned when I asked for one so there is that.
At lunchtime they serve a ridiculously large toritake set lunch. Recommended, though you might want to schedule a nap right after.
The nasi lemak at Hi Leskmi (#01-24) is super comforting.
Had the Royale With Cheese hoping for a classic burger but the BBQ sauce spoiled an otherwise good thing. Next time I will build my own. Omakase is still my number one but this is a decent second.
Michelin 2016 Bib Gourmand selection. Juicy beef, chewy noodle, hearty broth. Very yes.
Hong Kee Beef Noodle at #01-42 is a huge rec. Juicy beef, chewy noodle, hearty broth. Michelin-recognized to boot!

formattedAddress: 7 Maxwell Rd (Telok Ayer St / Amoy St)

tip.text: Had a pho bo dac biet and thoroughly enjoyed it. Spring rolls (goi cuon) also nice. My dining company was enthusiastic about the bun thit nuong cha gio. Only downside was slightly flaky service.
Brews are okay but come from Alpha Dominche machines—which in my opinion takes the fun out of the specialty coffee thing. Serving as pictured with a ridiculously small mug which hampers tasting. Meh.
Solid filter coffee but this place seems to be more about the food. Insanely swanky interior. A bit too clinical for my tastes.
Interesting spot to visit because of the vintage seventies mall it is part of. Mutton soup and ban mian are both worth the trek.

formattedAddress: Lvl 4, Beauty World Centre (144 Upper Bukit Timah Rd)

tip.text: Their stack of pancakes is indeed a proper stack. I've had better but wouldn't mind another one. Lavender latte is a bit weird but sort of works. Too bad they don't do pour over coffee.
As with the other branches: sushi is correct and affordable. Hits the sweet spot for me.
Surprisingly clean and delicate ramen.
Definitely worth a visit. Attractive interior, solid service, reasonable prices and tasty, well-presented contemporary interpretations of Singapore flavors. Go.
Cozy little coffee place with a very friendly and knowledge barista. Serves great pour over filter coffee. Beans sourced from some of the best Balinese roasters. Each order comes with a mini donut!
Tasty and attractive bowls but not as filling as they should be given the price tag (just south of twenty bucks if you add carbs or extra greens).
Taro spring rolls best avoided. Vegetarian tom yum dumpling soup nice and spicy. Pad thai not bad but a bit OTT. Interior is spacious, bright, clean and contemporary. All in all okay but not great.
Delightful place. Get a seat at the top floor and watch the bikes flow past along the river while feasting on such house specialties as spicy stir fried chicken ovaries with onion (!)
Went here for lunch a couple of times with local friends and was served a nice spread each time. The menu changes daily.
I can't tell you what I had exactly (locals brought me here) but the taste was great and I loved the cozy atmosphere.
I've tried a couple of branches now and the experience has always been good. Quality food at reasonable prices. Great place to get into dim sum if you're a newbie.
Had perfectly fine nasi lemak and popiah here. Probably the best lunch option in Funan DigitaLife Mall.

formattedAddress: #01-17, Funan Digitalife Mall (109 North Bridge Rd)

tip.text: Go mutton biryani or go bust. Service is so brisk it's not exactly a great place for a relaxed meal but I do keep returning for the food.
Love that they still use charcoal for the steamboat. We were a party of four and ordered the pomfret along with a few extras and had quite the feast.
Don't expect atmosphere but the 100% chicken broth toripaitan ramen is a welcome change from the ubiquitous tonkotsu.
Huge, many great stalls but A Noodle Story deserves a special mention for their Singapore-style ramen, which sounds like a ridiculous idea but turns out to be very tasty and value for money.

formattedAddress: 7 Maxwell Rd (Telok Ayer St / Amoy St)

tip.text: Had a tasty affordable dim sum lunch here. Service is very efficient. It's just outside the touristy part and frequented by locals.
My mango shaved ice wasn't bad but I am told the real deal can be found at Mei Heong Yuen one street over.
Generous serving of pork ribs and broth is nice and strong. Thicker than the one at Founder down the road. Hard to say which one I prefer.

venue.name: Ng Ah Sio Pork Ribs Soup Eating House

tip.text: Had a serviceable saba set from the Korean stall. Place is a bit cramped and gets insanely busy during weekday lunch hour. Vegetarian stall seemingly very popular.
A cozy suburban hawker center that gets pretty crowded and during weekday lunch hour. Had a very satisfying, spicy and cheap bowl of laksa here.
Tonkatsu is great. Crispy crust, tender meat, not greasy at all. Quality stuff.
Pretentious interior, lighting so low I almost took out my flashlight and coffee roasted to cinders (Italian style) all add up to an experience I'd rather not repeat.
Unremarkable kopitiam with one exception: there is an excellent yong tau foo stall in here.
The mutton biryani I ordered nearly killed me, it was that generous. Good thing I also ordered buttered naan. 😵

formattedAddress: 88 Syed Alwi Rd (92-98 Kampong Kapor Rd (Royal Indian Hotel))

tip.text: If you feel like splurging, treat yourself to a 12 SGD pork ribs and prawn mee soup. I had mine with the noodles on the side and was one happy camper.
If you can get over the fact that they're huge sea snails, the abalone noodles are quite a treat.
People queue at Kok Kee Wanton Noodle for good reason.
Delightful if humble fare with good vegetarian options. We had daal and aloo matta with our chapati. Cost next to nothing.
Good place for a big breakfast or brunch on the weekends. That's assuming you're not afraid of some cholesterol.
This place operates like Swiss clockwork. Hygiene is impeccable, service is fast but friendly and the food: wow. My Mysore style masala dosa was crazy tasty. I could have easily gone for seconds.
The local friend who brought me here insisted on sharing a ginger spring onion frog claypot. Surprisingly tasty when paired with a rice porridge.

formattedAddress: 265 New Bridge Rd. (Keong Saik Rd. (Ann Kway Building))

tip.text: Staff is uncommonly service oriented and the space is attractive. Good place for a couple of drinks in the evening.
My cheese burger was damn juicy and very tasty. Appreciated I could order it rare. If and when I crave a burger again I know where I will be going. Namely, here.
Oh man Hitachino Nest beer from the tap? Dangerous.
There are some seriously stunning pieces of Buddhist and Hindu art on display here.
My tuna melt was edible but didn't really make me happy. I guess I just shouldn't eat sandwiches in SG.
Gets pretty fucking busy during weekday lunch hour. For good reason. The wantan mee at stall 48 is indeed the bees knees.

venue.name: Hong Lim Complex Market & Food Centre

tip.text: I did what some tipsters here suggest and got the ajitama ramen and an order of gyoza. I wasn't sorry.
If you're in for something filling get the Ma Bo Lor Mee. A sticky, spicy thick brothed noodle dish. I added fried fish to mine for some extra protein.
Come here after sundown and feel like you're walking on a science fiction movie set. There is a light and music show every night and it is cheesy as hell but fun nonetheless.

formattedAddress: Gardens By The Bay (18 Marina Gardens Dr.)

tip.text: If you don't care for satay or just feel like a healthy meal for a change I can recommend getting the thunder tea rice. Rice with lots of veggies that comes with a herb-laden broth to mix it with.
The set meals are tasty and a steal. Mine was a saba shioyaki and it made me very happy.
OMG their naan fresh from the tandoor is the best.
Oh boy this place offers huge value. The food is super tasty, portions are generous and the atmosphere is very local. I had a rice meal. I want to go again.
Attractive interior although you might find it is trying too hard to look steampunk industrial even though you're in a mall. The coffee is prepared correctly but the taste is underwhelming.
I don't see much love for this food court in the tips but let me tell you two things: the yong tau foo is tasty and the guy preparing it is super kind and cheerful.

formattedAddress: Lv 4, City Square Mall (180 Kitchener Rd.)

tip.text: I really want to like this place. It's small, cozy and a bit rambunctious. Staff is upbeat. But the single origin pour over coffee is hugely incorrect. Super dark and over extracted. Stick to beer.
The eponymous pork chop is lean and tender and has a nice crispy crust. Affordable too. I say go.

venue.name: Supreme Pork Chop Rice 一品排骨饭

tip.text: This place is so huge, a man with an appetite can get in serious trouble here.
The tori miso ramen has a crazy rich broth. You'll want to take a nap after.
The sliced fish soup at stall 37 appears to be a lunchtime favorite. Rightly so.
If you don't mind not being right on the beach this is a great option for staying in Pemuteran. Gorgeous garden setting, super friendly staff and great food.
Simple, tasty, affordable Javanese lunch buffet. I was so spoiled for choice I had to go for seconds. Perfect really.
Get the ikan laut bakar and sop ikan laut. Make sure you order it 'pedas'. Seriously flavorsome and crazy fresh. You're shown the catch of the day from which to make your choice.
Warung with lots of seating and one of those menus that goes on and on. Be smart and pick one of the dishes people seem to come here for listed above the kitchen. Mine was a delectable nasi pecel.
Many people seem to come for the pecel. The nasi rames with smoked and fried lele is also nice.
Hands down the best place in town to have a proper meal for lunch (a rarity in NL) made with care using delicious ingredients.
To get to "Kalguksu Alley", take exit 5 from Hoehyeon Station. Upon exiting, turn right, and walk a short distance. The entrance is on your left hand side.
Leave the crowds behind and pop into Simsimhan for a tour of the house and a cup of tea.
Their jeongsik multi-course banquet includes a lot of fresh seasonal vegetables. Maybe not entirely traditional but a real treat. Unless you're a very big eater, I would go for the smallest menu.
In a city where most Mexican food is a sham, this tiny cantina and takeaway does a good job of offering dishes that are both tasty and correct.

venue.name: KANT - Kreuzberg Academy for Nerdery and Tinkering
KANT - Kreuzberg Academy for Nerdery and Tinkering

tip.text: These folks source their own wine so there's always something special on offer. Great for a quick glass if you have something to celebrate.
Super tasty sandwiches made with great artisanal bread and local ingredients. Lovely staff, too.
